     Running `target/debug/ecaz --help`
ecaz — corpus loading, benchmarking (recall / latency / storage), and cross-engine comparison for the Ecaz Postgres vector extension. Access methods (ec_hnsw, ec_ivf, ec_diskann) are selected via `--profile`; every command is profile-aware.

Usage: ecaz [OPTIONS] <COMMAND>

Commands:
  corpus   Corpus plumbing: load fixtures, inspect what's loaded, verify manifests
  bench    Benchmarks against a loaded corpus (recall, latency, storage, ...)
  compare  Compare Ecaz against external vector-search engines on the same corpus
  dev      Development/setup/test helpers that own the old wrapper-script surface
  quant    Offline quantizer feasibility / recall studies (no DB required)
  stress   Correctness-under-load harnesses (vacuum concurrency, crash recovery, ...)
  help     Print this message or the help of the given subcommand(s)

Options:
      --database <DATABASE>
          PostgreSQL database name. Defaults to $PGDATABASE or 'tqvector_bench'
          
          [env: PGDATABASE=]
          [default: tqvector_bench]

      --host <HOST>
          PostgreSQL host name or Unix socket directory
          
          [env: PGHOST=]

      --port <PORT>
          PostgreSQL port
          
          [env: PGPORT=]

      --user <USER>
          PostgreSQL user name
          
          [env: PGUSER=]

      --password <PASSWORD>
          PostgreSQL password. Prefer `.pgpass` for non-local use
          
          [env: PGPASSWORD]

      --log-file <LOG_FILE>
          Mirror CLI stdout/stderr into a file for packet-local artifact capture. Progress bars are suppressed so the file stays stable and diffable

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

  -V, --version
          Print version
